        Approved — fat compound: fungal oils, tasted like damp earth. Approved. Vitamin complex, attempt one — bitter, possibly toxic, by Remedy's concerned analysis of her face. Rejected. Vitamin complex, attempt two — less bitter, questionable. Approved with reservations.

        Hours blurred together.

        Her stomach had moved past hunger into hollow, aching emptiness — lightheaded, shaky; the small test samples weren't nearly enough.

        Finally — «finally» — Remedy said, "All compounds tested and approved. Ready for full meal synthesis."

        Holloway said, "Meal preparation will take approximately forty-five minutes. Per nutrition protocol, first meal should be a modest portion to avoid digestive distress after extended fasting."

        Kira wanted to cry or scream — or both.

        Kira repeated, "Forty-five minutes."

        Remedy said, "I'm already growing the full batch." The chamber was filled with mushrooms now — dozens of varieties in various stages of fruiting. "Need to harvest, process, and combine compounds properly. Chemistry takes time."

        Kira echoed, "Chemistry takes time."

        Scout pressed harder against her leg.

        She could wait forty-five more minutes; she'd waited hours already. What was forty-five more minutes? Eternity, apparently.

        ¶

        But Remedy was working — robot moving between mushroom clusters, harvesting, processing, combining compounds in salvaged containers. The mushrooms decomposed back into the network after harvest, nutrients recycled. Efficient.

        Holloway filled the time with final documentation: meal schedule recommendations, nutritional goal setting, future dietary assessment timelines.

        Kira stopped listening. She just watched Remedy work. Chemistry. Actual food being made.

        Finally, the robot approached with a container.

        Remedy announced, "Nutritionally complete meal — protein, carbohydrates, fats, approximate vitamins. Total: about eight hundred calories. Not optimized for flavor — couldn't spare the compounds for taste enhancement. But it's food. *It won't kill you.* Probably makes you _not die_, actually."

        The container held grayish-brown paste mixed with chunks of processed mushroom and some kind of plant fiber. It looked like institutional food that had lost a fight with despair.

        Kira had never wanted anything more in her life.

        Kira said, "Thank you."

        She meant it completely.

        She ate. It tasted like mushroom paste mixed with cardboard, flavored with existential ennui and a hint of earth. The texture was somewhere between wallpaper paste and failed protein bars.

        It was the best meal she'd ever had.

        Her body recognized «food» — actual nutrition entering her system after thirty-six hours of nothing. The hollowness began to fill. The shaking eased. Her brain started functioning properly again.

        Scout bounced happily, clearly relieved.

        Holloway said, "Digestive tolerance check in thirty minutes. Then we can establish regular meal schedule — three times daily, modest portions until your body readjusts."
      </text>
